>     v->y = 240-SCALE*v->y*(v->iz);
>     v->z = ((kzen/v->z)+z0)/65536.f;
> }
> 
> This doesn't seem to a projection as I've learnt it at Uni.  The most
> confusing part is the v->z assignment which is based on the somewhat
> bizarre constants kzen & z0 which are defined as:

Well, usually university projections stop after the v->y assignment. The
projection of the x and y coordinates is a simple division by z (or a
multiplication by 1/z in this case). 
 
> const float Back  = 40.0;
> const float Front = 0.5;
> 
> #define kzen (-65535.0*(Back*Front)/(Back-Front))
> #define z0   ( 65535.0*Back/(Back-Front))
> 
> What on earth is this doing?

A normalisation of Z Coordinates in a very obfuscated, from-the-book way.
kzen is the Center of the Z range. It basically brings z into the range
+/- 1 around the center.

I would rather have a look at the engine demo, the code is much cleaner.

> Other strangeness is that it would seem that the homogenous coordinate 
> system I was taught isn't being used.  If I did a 3d engine using
> homogenous coordinates how would this reflect on Warp3D?

The homogenous coordinate W that is usually used in 3D graphics does not
have too much to do with that used in Warp3D. You should simply set the W
coordinate to something like n/z, where n can be almost anything greater
than 1 (say, n=10.0), but you have to make sure this is the Z from the
camera space, i.e. before perspective projection.

If you are thinking OpenGL'ish, you can actually use 1/w as the W
coordinate.

If you still have problems, you might want to wait for the Release of
MiniGL, this encapsulates all the dirty stuff like transformation, texture
management, double/triplebuffering, perspective-corrected mapping, and a
few other things. It will probably be released this months...

> Additionally, I presume that there is no view vector normalisation as we
> are looking straight at the object.  Is this correct?

No, there is no camera involved, so the view vector is basically always
(0,0,1)'

> Has anyone got any pointers as to how I can turn my somewhat flat shapes
> into glorious 3d-o-vision??

You mean like lathe or sweep? You should find something like that under
those keywords in a search engine... No pointers, sorry ;)

> On a slightly different tack - how does Warp3D allocate it's texture colours?
> Is it up to the user to do so?  If not, is there a way of restricting the
> colours it allocates?

It doesn't allocate any colors in the sense of obtaining a pen or so.
Textures are almost always RGB true color, either 15, 16, 24 or 32 bits.
Currently no driver uses paletted textures (the virge because it doesn't
support them, the Permedia because you would have to reload the entire
palette each time). You can pass in paletted data, but that will get
converted by Warp3D...

