> Ok, let's assume i've understand this lightmap-crap... and let's assume i've
> got a way to precalculate the lightmap's in QMap (what the original source
> does in any way...) but i see no possibility to draw bigger surfaces with
> repeated textures and steched light(alpha-)maps in one pass i.e. give the
> texture and the alphamap different u/v-coordinates... u know help (a second
> pass is NOT what i want to hear ;)

You have to repeat the texture in the cache. For instance, you hava a
texture cache with 256x256 textures. If the texture you want to use (the
one that is repeated) is, say 64x64, you just copy it into the texture
cache multiple times, mix in the lightmap, and use the u/v coordinates of
the lightmap when drawing the polygon. If the texture doesn't fit multiple
times, you have to scale it down, or, even better, use a mimap for that
purpose. The problem here is that you have to limit the texture cache
size, for speed reasons, and because you can pre-allocate the texture
objects in Warp3D, and use W3D_UpdateTexImage to move a cache entry to the
graphics board.

You can also use one texture cache entry for multiple textures, as the
resulting textures (with lightmaps) aren't repeated anymore. 

It's a very complex subject, and something that's hard to find any good
information on. I remember a paper (don't know the URL, sorry) that was
called "The KAGE surface caching algorithm", that describes surface
caching in detail..... I'll see if I have the URL somewhere, and post it
here...

