Well, the point seems to be that you want to have, say, a 128x128 texture
for "graphics" and a say 32x32 texture for lightmapping (they are usually
much smaller). You have to use different texture coordinates, but
otherwise there is no problem (assuming two-pass rendering is used...)

> What's KAGE? And i haven't yet understand how this texture caching should
> work an what's the advantage...
> Maybe this is what i have to understand...

KAGE is a 3D engine. There was some web page about it, but I can't
remember the URL... It was a quite well-known company that did it,
though...

Surface caching works thus: A "surface" (also in Quake terms) is the
one single polygon in the scene plus its texture map plus its lightmap.
Many polygons may share the same texture map, and even share the same
lightmap, but usually this isn't the case. surface caching works by
"manually" (i.e. with the CPU) applying the lightmap to the texture map in
the appropriate way (i.e. with proper u/v coordniates) so that the
resulting texture map can be applied to the polygon in the scene. This
resulting map is of course more or less unique to this specific polygon,
so basically quite a lot of texture maps might be required/get created
this way. Since the video ram usually is not big enough to hold them all,
they are cached, much like "normal" textures are cached...
 
